24/01/2007
SKOPJE, Macedonia -- The country's Security Council met on Tuesday (January 23rd) to discuss the latest challenges confronting Macedonia.
During the session, President Branko Crvenkovski said the Council believes that no risks to stability, security or territorial integrity would stem from the decision on Kosovo's future status.
Acknowledging some uncertainty related to extremist criminal groups and large quantities of weapons in Kosovo, he stressed that Macedonian security services are constantly monitoring the situation and are prepared to act promptly if necessary.
Prime Minister Nikola Gruevski agreed that there are no current threats to stability and security.
(Vecer - 23/01/07;
MIA, Makfax, Telma TV, A1 TV - 22/01/07)
